          </h2>
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-300 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
            Get answers to common questions about our SaaS development services
          </p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="grid gap-6 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
          {[
            {
              question: "What is the typical timeline for SaaS development?",
              answer: "SaaS development typically takes 6-12 months depending on complexity. This includes MVP development, testing, launch, and initial iterations. We use agile methodologies to deliver working features incrementally and gather user feedback early."
            },
            {
              question: "How do you handle SaaS scalability and performance?",
              answer: "We build SaaS applications with scalability in mind using cloud-native architectures, microservices, auto-scaling, and performance optimization. We also implement monitoring and analytics to track performance and user behavior."
            },
            {
              question: "What about SaaS security and compliance?",
              answer: "We implement enterprise-grade security including data encryption, secure authentication, regular security audits, and compliance with industry standards (SOC 2, GDPR, HIPAA, etc.). We also provide security documentation and certifications."
            },
            {
              question: "Do you help with SaaS pricing and monetization strategies?",
              answer: "Yes, we help design subscription models, pricing tiers, payment integration, and monetization strategies. We also implement analytics to track user behavior and optimize pricing based on usage patterns."
            },
            {
              question: "How do you handle SaaS updates and maintenance?",
              answer: "We provide continuous deployment, automated testing, and regular updates. We also offer 24/7 monitoring, backup systems, and disaster recovery to ensure your SaaS platform runs smoothly with minimal downtime."
            },
            {
              question: "Can you integrate with existing business systems?",
              answer: "Absolutely! We specialize in integrating SaaS platforms with existing business systems including CRM, ERP, accounting software, and third-party APIs. This ensures seamless data flow and operational efficiency."
            }
          ].map((faq, index) => (
            <div class="bg-white/5 backdrop-blur-sm border border-white/10 rounded-lg p-6">
              <button 
                class="w-full text-left flex justify-between items-center"
                onclick={`toggleFAQ(${index})`}
                aria-expanded="false"
              >
                <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white pr-4">{faq.question}</h3>
                <svg class="w-5 h-5 text-primary-400 transform transition-transform duration-200" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7" />
                </svg>
              </button>
              <div id={`faq-answer-${index}`} class="hidden mt-4">
                <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">{faq.answer}</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- FAQ Schema -->
    <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "What is the typical timeline for SaaS development?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "SaaS development typically takes 6-12 months depending on complexity. This includes MVP development, testing, launch, and initial iterations. We use agile methodologies to deliver working features incrementally and gather user feedback early."
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How do you handle SaaS scalability and performance?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
